The paper proposes a boosting algorithm with explicit regularization and evaluates it on public datasets commonly used for benchmarking boosting algorithms. This suggests that the paper belongs to the machine learning (cs.LG) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. The use of distributed classical heuristic optimizer as a stand-in for quantum hardware and the discussion of emerging quantum optimization technology suggests that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and emerging technologies (cs.ET) sub-categories. Finally, the discussion of combinatorial optimization problems suggests that the paper may also belong to the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
